{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501386"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:28:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:28:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1756"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1756"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.08,0.04,0.71,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1756"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52081"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1756"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1756"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37398"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2967"},{"type":"tags","id":"4847"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4108"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9899"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15114"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52081"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-week history of increasing constipation, abdominal pain, insomnia, and increased urinary frequency (approximately eight voids a day). He has a medical history of metastatic lung cancer. He does not take any regular medications. His wife, who accompanies him, reports moderate confusion that is not affected by the time of day. On examination, he appears unwell with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals mild generalised tenderness. There is no bony tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urinary tract infection","Brain metastases","Opioid side effects","Hypercalcaemia","Diabetes insipidus"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypercalcaemia\u003C/strong\u003E, a well-recognised complication of metastatic cancer, particularly lung cancer. The classic symptoms of hypercalcaemia include constipation, polyuria (increased urinary frequency), confusion, and fatigue - often summarised as \u0027bones, stones, groans, and psychiatric overtones\u0027. All of these symptoms are present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary tract infection\u003C/strong\u003E could explain the increased urinary frequency but would not account for the constipation, abdominal pain, or confusion. Additionally, there\u0027s no mention of dysuria or fever, which are common in UTIs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrain metastases\u003C/strong\u003E could potentially cause confusion, but would not explain the gastrointestinal and urinary symptoms. Furthermore, confusion from brain metastases would likely be progressive rather than stable throughout the day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpioid side effects\u003C/strong\u003E could potentially cause constipation and confusion. However, there\u0027s no mention of the patient being on opioids, and opioids wouldn\u0027t explain the increased urinary frequency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetes insipidus\u003C/strong\u003E could cause polyuria but wouldn\u0027t explain the constipation, abdominal pain, or confusion. Moreover, it\u0027s a rare complication of lung cancer compared to hypercalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the patient\u0027s history of metastatic lung cancer and the constellation of symptoms (constipation, polyuria, confusion), hypercalcaemia is the most likely diagnosis. It\u0027s important to note that hypercalcaemia can occur in malignancy due to osteolytic bone metastases, tumor secretion of parathyroid hormone-related protein (PTHrP), or rarely, ectopic parathyroid hormone (PTH) production. Prompt recognition and treatment of hypercalcaemia is crucial, as it can lead to significant morbidity if left untreated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypercalcaemia is a well-recognised complication associated with metastatic bone disease.","Classic symptoms of hypercalcaemia include constipation, polyuria, confusion, and fatigue, often summarised as \u0027bones, stones, groans, and psychiatric overtones\u0027."],"references":["Zagzag J, Hu MI, Fisher SB, et al. Hypercalcemia and Cancer: Differential Diagnosis and Treatment. Ca Cancer J Clin 2018;68:377-86. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30240520/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37398"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1756"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37398"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-02T11:39:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-02T11:41:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1756"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52081"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"gro